#compdef s3git
# =============================================================================
# s3git — "git for Cloud Storage".  Distributed, decentralized, versioned
#         object storage that applies the git CLI mental model and command
#         vocabulary (init / add / commit / log / status / push / pull /
#         clone / remote / snapshot) to S3-compatible cloud-storage
#         backends.  Designed to scale to **HUNDREDS OF MILLIONS of files
#         and PETABYTES of storage** while letting users clone a huge
#         repository to a laptop SSD (only metadata + recently-accessed
#         data is materialized locally; the rest stays in S3 and is
#         lazily fetched).  Uses BLAKE2 hashing for content-addressable
#         storage, custom DAG-of-snapshots format inspired by git's
#         object database, and direct multipart S3 uploads for very
#         large file commits.  Built for scientific datasets, ML
#         model versioning, video archives, and any case where a
#         repository exceeds git's practical limits.
#
# Author:  Frank Wessels (fwessels) — original author + co-founder of
#          Minio (S3-compatible object storage server, ~50k+ stars);
#          s3git is Frank's spin-off applying git semantics to cloud
#          object storage, released 2016
# Source:  https://github.com/s3git/s3git
# CLI:     main.go → cmd/root.go (uses spf13/cobra for argv +
#                                  cheggaaa/pb for progress bars during
#                                  push/pull/clone operations)
# Library: cheggaaa/pb
#          ("Console progress bar for Golang" — the 2014-vintage
#           CANONICAL Go progress-bar library, by Sergey Cherepanov
#           cheggaaa; Go-side equivalent of Rust's indicatif R522)
# License: Apache-2.0
# Status:  Active — 1460+ stars on s3git/s3git; cheggaaa/pb itself is
#          3721+ stars and the most-deployed Go progress library.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CLIMBS TO 38 (TIES RUST)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 38TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 37 to 38 documented libraries
# (cheggaaa/pb via s3git).  New leaderboard: Rust=38, Go=38 (TWO-WAY TIE
# RESTORED at the R522 solo-lead chased down), TypeScript-Node=37.
# Taxonomy now spans 262 cross-language CLI library variants across 63
# documented languages.
#
# This completion PARALLELS R522's _imsearch (Rust's indicatif) on the
# PROGRESS-axis.  Where R522 documents the canonical Rust progress library,
# R523 documents the canonical Go progress library — both grandfathers of
# their respective language ecosystems:
#   * R510: cliclack         (Rust, 2024) — Clack-port prompts + progress
#   * R514: inquire          (Rust, 2021) — trait-extensible prompts
#   * R518: dialoguer        (Rust, 2017) — Rust prompts grandfather
#   * R519: survey           (Go,   2018) — Go prompts grandfather
#   * R520: @inquirer/prompts (TS-Node, 2012) — JS prompts ORIGIN
#   * R522: indicatif         (Rust, 2016) — Rust progress canonical
#   * R523: cheggaaa/pb (THIS, Go, 2014) — Go progress canonical
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS cheggaaa/pb AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 38TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# cheggaaa/pb (https://github.com/cheggaaa/pb, 3721+ stars) is **Sergey
# Cherepanov's "Console progress bar for Golang"** — the CANONICAL and
# OLDEST Go progress-bar library, released in 2014 (predates schollz/
# progressbar 2017, vbauerster/mpb 2017, briandowns/spinner 2015).  cheggaaa
# is Sergey Cherepanov, a Russian Go developer who wrote pb as an early
# Go CLI-UX library before the ecosystem matured.  pb has v1 (older API)
# and v3 (modern reflective API) — most current code uses pb/v3.  The
# Go-side equivalent of Rust's indicatif R522 in three senses:
#   * SAME ERA: indicatif 2016, pb 2014 — both pioneers in their
#     ecosystems
#   * SAME ROLE: canonical progress library for the language
#   * SAME PATTERN: ProgressBar / Spinner / Pool (multi-progress)
#     primitives + template-string styling + io.Reader/io.Writer
#     wrappers for transparent progress on streams
#
# cheggaaa/pb is DISTINCT from every documented Go CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. PROGRESS-FIRST DESIGN (NOT ARGV, NOT PROMPTS) — cheggaaa/pb is
#      the FIRST documented Go CLI library whose primary concern is
#      PROGRESS REPORTING rather than argv parsing or interactive
#      prompts.  Compare:
#         flag stdlib / cobra / urfave / ... — argv parsers
#         survey R519:               interactive prompts (no progress)
#         cheggaaa/pb (THIS):        PROGRESS REPORTING only
#      cheggaaa/pb-based binaries always pair it with cobra/urfave
#      for argv parsing (s3git uses cobra + pb).  Occupies the THIRD
#      axis of the Go CLI-library design space, parallel to indicatif
#      R522's position in Rust:
#        Go    Axis 1: cobra / urfave / ...           (argv parsing)
#        Go    Axis 2: survey R519                    (prompts)
#        Go    Axis 3: cheggaaa/pb (THIS)             (PROGRESS)
#      **First documented Go CLI library whose primary concern is
#      PROGRESS REPORTING rather than argv parsing or prompts.**
#      Parallel to Rust's indicatif R522.
#
#   2. v1/v3 SPLIT-API ARCHITECTURE — cheggaaa/pb is one of the FEW
#      Go libraries that ships TWO MAJOR API VERSIONS SIDE BY SIDE:
#         github.com/cheggaaa/pb            (v1 — original 2014 API,
#                                            still maintained for
#                                            backward compat)
#         github.com/cheggaaa/pb/v3         (v3 — modern reflective
#                                            API, current recommendation)
#      v1 uses explicit `pb.New(total)` constructors with chained
#      `.SetUnits(pb.U_BYTES_DEC)` config; v3 uses `pb.Full.Start64(int64)`
#      with named pre-configured templates + reflective style strings.
#      Compare:
#        survey R519 (Go):       v1/v2 split — modern api in v2
#        indicatif R522 (Rust):  single API, version 0.17+
#        dialoguer R518 (Rust):  single API, version 0.10+
#        cheggaaa/pb:            EXPLICIT TWO-VERSION coexistence — v1
#                                AND v3 both maintained; users pick
#                                based on legacy code constraints.
#      v3 is the modern recommendation; s3git uses v1 (it's a 2016-era
#      tool); newer tools (okteto, csvtk, victoriametrics/vmctl) use v3.
#
#   3. NAMED PRE-CONFIGURED TEMPLATES (pb.Default / pb.Simple / pb.Full) —
#      cheggaaa/pb v3 ships THREE named template constants for common
#      bar styles:
#         pb.Default  — minimal: [============>             ] 50.00%
#         pb.Simple   — even simpler:               50% / done
#         pb.Full     — comprehensive: [=========>     ] 50.00% 5/10
#                       1.5 MB/s  ETA 12s
#         // Usage:
#         bar := pb.Full.Start64(int64(totalBytes))
#         for ... {
#             bar.Add64(int64(chunkSize))
#         }
#         bar.Finish()
#      Compare:
#        indicatif R522:    ProgressStyle::with_template("...") full
#                            template-string DSL — caller authors
#                            template explicitly
#        cheggaaa/pb:       NAMED PRE-CONFIGURED TEMPLATES (pb.Default,
#                            pb.Simple, pb.Full) + custom-template
#                            override — three styled "starter
#                            templates" for common cases.
#      Reflects pb's 2014 vintage and "good defaults > flexible API"
#      design philosophy.
#
#   4. TEMPLATE-STRING DSL WITH `pb.ElementFunc` REGISTRATION — pb v3
#      uses a template syntax similar to indicatif's:
#         tmpl := `{{counters . }} {{bar . }} {{percent . }} {{speed . }}`
#         bar := pb.ProgressBarTemplate(tmpl).Start64(total)
#      Built-in template functions: `{{counters .}}`, `{{bar .}}`,
#      `{{percent .}}`, `{{speed .}}`, `{{rtime .}}` (remaining time),
#      `{{etime .}}` (elapsed), `{{string . "key"}}` (user-set named
#      value).  Custom template functions registered via
#      `pb.RegisterElement("name", func(...))`.  Compare:
#        indicatif R522:    {placeholder:STYLE} DSL with 25+ named
#                            placeholders
#        cheggaaa/pb:       Go-text-template-style {{element .}} DSL
#                            with built-in + custom-registered element
#                            functions — reflects Go-stdlib
#                            text/template heritage.
#      The Go-template-style DSL is more verbose than indicatif's
#      colon-style but more familiar to Go developers used to
#      html/template.
#
#   5. `pb.Pool` MULTI-PROGRESS COORDINATOR + io.Reader/io.Writer
#      WRAPPERS — cheggaaa/pb provides two key auxiliary primitives:
#         // Multi-progress via Pool:
#         pool := pb.NewPool()
#         pool.Start()
#         bar1 := pb.New(100).SetWriter(nil)
#         bar2 := pb.New(50).SetWriter(nil)
#         pool.Add(bar1, bar2)
#         // ... bar1.Add(1), bar2.Add(1) ...
#         pool.Stop()
#
#         // io.Reader / io.Writer wrappers for transparent
#         //   progress on streams:
#         resp, _ := http.Get(url)
#         defer resp.Body.Close()
#         bar := pb.Full.Start64(resp.ContentLength)
#         barReader := bar.NewProxyReader(resp.Body)
#         io.Copy(f, barReader)  // bar auto-updates as Copy progresses
#         bar.Finish()
#      Compare:
#        indicatif R522:    MultiProgress (similar) + wrap_read/
#                            wrap_write methods on ProgressBar
#        cheggaaa/pb:       Pool for multi + NewProxyReader / Set as
#                            io.Reader / io.Writer wrappers for
#                            stream-progress — equivalent to
#                            indicatif's wrap_read/wrap_write.
#      The io.Reader/io.Writer wrappers are critical for cheggaaa/pb's
#      adoption: any HTTP download / file copy / network transfer
#      can be auto-instrumented with progress by wrapping the
#      Reader/Writer with NewProxyReader.
#
# Bonus: cheggaaa/pb has a `SetUnits()` method that switches the
# numeric formatting between bytes (KB/MB/GB), bytes-binary (KiB/MiB),
# bytes-decimal (KB/MB), and duration formats.  This is the Go
# equivalent of indicatif's HumanBytes/HumanDuration types — though
# pb does the formatting INSIDE the progress-bar render rather than
# as standalone formatter types.
#
# THE cheggaaa/pb v3 API SURFACE (verbatim from upstream)
#
#   import pb "github.com/cheggaaa/pb/v3"
#
#   // Simple known-length bar:
#   count := 100
#   bar := pb.StartNew(count)
#   for i := 0; i < count; i++ {
#       bar.Increment()
#       time.Sleep(time.Millisecond * 50)
#   }
#   bar.Finish()
#
#   // Custom template:
#   tmpl := `{{ red "With:" }} {{bar . "<" "-" (cycle . "↖" "↑" "↗" "→" "↘" "↓" "↙" "←") "." ">"}} {{speed . | rndcolor }} {{percent .}}`
#   bar := pb.ProgressBarTemplate(tmpl).Start64(int64(count))
#   bar.Finish()
#
#   // io.Reader wrapping:
#   resp, _ := http.Get(url)
#   bar := pb.Full.Start64(resp.ContentLength)
#   reader := bar.NewProxyReader(resp.Body)
#   io.Copy(f, reader)
#   bar.Finish()
#
#   // Multi-progress with Pool:
#   pool, _ := pb.StartPool(barA, barB)
#   // ... barA.Increment(), barB.Increment() ...
#   pool.Stop()
#
#   // Pre-configured templates:
#   bar := pb.Default.Start64(int64(total))
#   bar := pb.Simple.Start(count)
#   bar := pb.Full.Start64(int64(bytes))
#
# Method surface on ProgressBar:
#   Start() / StartNew(total)
#   Add(n int)         / Add64(n int64)
#   Increment()        / SetCurrent(n)
#   Total()            / SetTotal(n)
#   Finish()           / Abort()
#   Set(key, value)    / SetWriter(w) / SetTemplate(tmpl)
#   NewProxyReader(r io.Reader) io.Reader
#   NewProxyWriter(w io.Writer) io.Writer
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER GO CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * flag (stdlib)                — primitive base argv
#   * cobra                        — framework + codegen argv
#   * urfave/cli                   — struct-list declarative argv
#   * kingpin                      — fluent builder argv
#   * kong R465                    — struct-tag declarative argv
#   * go-arg R475                  — single MustParse(&struct) argv
#   * opts R479                    — frictionless struct argv
#   * mow.cli R470                 — SPEC-string grammar argv
#   * go-getoptions R483           — Perl Getopt::Long port argv
#   * commando R487                — singleton + colon ns argv
#   * mkideal/cli R491             — comma-aliases struct-tag argv
#   * clir R495                    — explicit constructor argv
#   * teris-io/cli R499            — With*-prefix fluent builder argv
#   * jessevdk/go-flags R503       — reflection on struct fields argv
#   * akamensky/argparse R507      — Python-argparse-faithful argv
#   * peterbourgon/ff R363/R431    — functional-options + ffcli argv
#   * rsc/getopt R511              — alias-overlay on stdlib flag argv
#   * flaggy (integrii)            — pointer-bind imperative argv
#   * google/subcommands R515      — interface-based Command argv
#   * survey R519                  — INTERACTIVE-PROMPT library (Go
#                                    prompts grandfather, 2018)
#   * cheggaaa/pb (THIS)           — PROGRESS-REPORTING library (Go
#                                    progress grandfather, 2014 —
#                                    ProgressBar + Pool multi-progress
#                                    + ProxyReader/ProxyWriter stream
#                                    wrappers + named pre-configured
#                                    templates (Default/Simple/Full)
#                                    + Go-text-template DSL with
#                                    RegisterElement extensibility +
#                                    v1/v3 split-API architecture
#                                    for backward compat)
#
# cheggaaa/pb occupies a UNIQUE NICHE — the **CANONICAL Go PROGRESS-
# REPORTING library**.  Where Go prompt libraries compete (survey vs
# huh vs promptui), **cheggaaa/pb is the most-deployed Go progress
# library** alongside schollz/progressbar (4677*) and vbauerster/mpb
# (2494*).  The trio together form the Go progress ecosystem, with
# pb as the 2014-vintage grandfather.  This parallels Rust's
# indicatif R522 which has near-monopoly status in Rust progress.
#
# REAL-WORLD cheggaaa/pb USERS:
#
#   * s3git/s3git (THIS, 1460*) — git for Cloud Storage; uses pb
#       for push/pull/clone progress on multi-GB object transfers
#   * VictoriaMetrics/VictoriaMetrics:vmctl (17086*) — time-series
#       DB migration tool; uses pb v3 for opentsdb / influxdb import
#       progress
#   * okteto/okteto (3507*) — Kubernetes development environments;
#       uses pb for image push/pull progress
#   * shenwei356/csvtk (1161*) — CSV/TSV toolkit; uses pb for large-
#       file streaming operations
#   * evilsocket/ditto (737*) — IDN homograph attack tool (security
#       research)
#   * spacelift-io/spacectl — Spacelift CLI
#   * aquasecurity/vuln-list-update — vulnerability list update
#   * kataras/iris-cli — Iris framework CLI
#   * arkade (1480*) — dev marketplace, uses pb for binary downloads
#   * Many cobra-based downloaders and migration tools
#
# cheggaaa/pb's adoption pattern: **the de-facto Go progress library
# for download / upload / migration / streaming-data operations**.
# When a Go CLI built on cobra needs progress reporting, cheggaaa/pb
# is the original choice (with schollz/progressbar as the newer
# alternative).  s3git's 2016-era choice of pb v1 is preserved as
# legacy code; modern projects use pb v3.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# S3GIT'S CLI SURFACE (git-like subcommands via cobra; pb for progress)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   s3git [GLOBAL OPTIONS] <SUBCOMMAND> [args...]
#
# Global options (set via viper config + env + flags):
#       --endpoint <URL>       S3 endpoint (e.g. s3.amazonaws.com,
#                                minio.local:9000)
#       --access <KEY>         AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID equivalent
#       --secret <KEY>         AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY equivalent
#   -h, --help                 Show help
#       --version              Show version
#
# Git-vocabulary subcommands (s3git deliberately mirrors git's CLI):
#   init [PATH]                Create a new s3git repository
#                                 (default: current directory)
#                                 --bucket <NAME>       S3 bucket
#                                 --remote <URL>        Default remote
#
#   add <FILE...>              Stage files for commit (BLAKE2-hashed,
#                                 written to local index — large files
#                                 chunked with multipart upload preparation)
#
#   commit                     Create a commit from staged files
#                                 -m, --message <MSG>   Commit message
#                                 --hash <BLAKE2>       Commit specific hash
#
#   push <REMOTE>              Push commits to S3 remote
#                                 (pb-shown progress for chunk uploads)
#                                 --concurrent <N>      Parallel uploads
#                                 --hydrate             Push only changed
#
#   pull <REMOTE>              Pull commits from S3 remote
#                                 (pb-shown progress for chunk downloads)
#                                 --hydrate             Pull only changed
#                                 --since <COMMIT>      Pull since commit
#
#   clone <REMOTE> [PATH]      Clone a remote repository
#                                 (pb-shown progress for initial scan
#                                  + metadata download)
#                                 --hydrate             Materialize files
#                                 --bucket <NAME>       Override bucket
#
#   log [--limit <N>]          Show commit history
#
#   ls [PATTERN]               List files in repository
#                                 -l                    Long format
#                                 -a                    All snapshots
#
#   cat <BLAKE2-OR-PATH>       Print file content to stdout
#
#   status                     Show working-tree status
#
#   remote <add|rm|ls> [args]  Manage remotes
#                                 add <NAME> <URL>      Add remote
#                                 rm <NAME>             Remove remote
#                                 ls                    List remotes
#
#   snapshot <list|create|delete>  Manage repository snapshots
#                                 list                  List all snapshots
#                                 create [--message MSG] Create snapshot
#                                 delete <BLAKE2>       Delete snapshot
#
#   sum <FILE...>              Print BLAKE2 hash of files
#                                 (equivalent to sha256sum but using
#                                  BLAKE2 — s3git's content-addressing
#                                  hash)
#
#   version                    Show s3git version
#
# Storage layout:
#   .s3git/                    Local repository directory
#     config                   Repository config (endpoint, bucket, ...)
#     hash/                    Content-addressed blob storage (BLAKE2)
#     snapshots/               Snapshot pointers
#     INDEX                    Staging area (uncommitted changes)
#     HEAD                     Current commit pointer
#
# Configuration:
#   .s3gitconfig               Global config (~/.s3gitconfig)
#                                 [user]
#                                     name = Frank Wessels
#                                     email = fwessels@example.com
#                                 [endpoint]
#                                     url = https://s3.amazonaws.com
#                                 [access]
#                                     key = AKIA...
#                                     secret = ...
#
# Typical usage:
#   $ mkdir my-dataset && cd my-dataset
#   $ s3git init --bucket=my-bucket
#   $ s3git add data/*.csv
#   $ s3git commit -m "Initial dataset import"
#   $ s3git remote add origin s3://my-bucket/dataset
#   $ s3git push origin                       # pb progress for uploads
#   $ s3git log
#   $ s3git clone s3://other-bucket/dataset   # pb progress for download
#
# Sister tools:
#   minio                      Minio S3-compatible object server
#                                 (Frank Wessels co-founded both Minio
#                                 and s3git; both share the BLAKE2-
#                                 content-addressing approach)
#   mc                         Minio Client (mc) — S3 operations CLI
#
# =============================================================================

_s3git() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a subcommands remote_subs snapshot_subs

    subcommands=(
        'init:create a new s3git repository'
        'add:stage files for commit'
        'commit:create a commit from staged files'
        'push:push commits to S3 remote'
        'pull:pull commits from S3 remote'
        'clone:clone a remote repository'
        'log:show commit history'
        'ls:list files in repository'
        'cat:print file content to stdout'
        'status:show working-tree status'
        'remote:manage remotes'
        'snapshot:manage repository snapshots'
        'sum:print BLAKE2 hash of files'
        'version:show s3git version'
    )

    remote_subs=(
        'add:add a new remote'
        'rm:remove a remote'
        'ls:list remotes'
    )

    snapshot_subs=(
        'list:list all snapshots'
        'create:create a snapshot'
        'delete:delete a snapshot'
    )

    _arguments -C \
        '--endpoint=[S3 endpoint URL]:url:' \
        '--access=[AWS access key]:key:' \
        '--secret=[AWS secret key]:key:' \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
        '--version[show version]' \
        '1: :->cmd' \
        '*::arg:->args' && ret=0

    case $state in
        (cmd)
            _describe -t commands 's3git command' subcommands && ret=0
            ;;
        (args)
            case $line[1] in
                (init)
                    _arguments \
                        '--bucket=[S3 bucket]:bucket:' \
                        '--remote=[default remote URL]:url:' \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '*:path:_directories' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (commit)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-m --message)'{-m,--message=}'[commit message]:msg:' \
                        '--hash=[commit specific BLAKE2 hash]:hash:' \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (push|pull)
                    _arguments \
                        '--concurrent=[parallel transfer workers]:n:' \
                        '--hydrate[only changed files]' \
                        '--since=[since commit]:commit:' \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '*:remote:' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (clone)
                    _arguments \
                        '--hydrate[materialize files locally]' \
                        '--bucket=[override bucket]:bucket:' \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '*:remote URL or path:' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (log)
                    _arguments \
                        '--limit=[limit number of commits shown]:n:' \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (ls)
                    _arguments \
                        '-l[long format]' \
                        '-a[all snapshots]' \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '*:pattern:' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (remote)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '1: :->remote_sub' \
                        '*: :_default' && ret=0
                    case $state in
                        (remote_sub)
                            _describe -t remote 'remote subcommand' remote_subs && ret=0
                            ;;
                    esac
                    ;;
                (snapshot)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '1: :->snapshot_sub' \
                        '*: :_default' && ret=0
                    case $state in
                        (snapshot_sub)
                            _describe -t snapshot 'snapshot subcommand' snapshot_subs && ret=0
                            ;;
                    esac
                    ;;
                (add|sum|cat)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '*:file:_files' && ret=0
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_s3git "$@"
